<h3><center>Research</center></h3>
<div>
<h4><center>{*}Setup a Linux USB/CD bootable drive{*}</center></h4>
        <u>Items needed for Linux:<br></u>
        * An internet Connection.<br>
        * <a href="https://www.belena.io/etcher/">BelenaEtcher</a>, <a href="universal-usb-install.en.softonic.com"> UUSBI</a>, DD (Linux: dd=if/dev/XImageOfDistro of=/dev/sdx). <br>
        * <a href="www.ubuntu.com/download">Ubuntu</a> || <a href="www.linuxmint.com/download.php">Mint</a> || <a href="manjaro.org/get-manjaro/">Manjaro</a><br>
        * USB/MicroSD device ~4gb+ (Dependent on Distro size).<br>
        * Separate computer (One to put Linux on).
          <br>
          <br>
          <p>
       For this tutorial I will be using the software Etcher for flashing the USB drive. I have read that the dd Linux command works wonders(dd=if/dev/XImageOfDistro of=/dev/sdx). I have not have a whole lot of success with flashing .iso files onto USB drives with the dd command but I have read stories explaining it's <a href="">importance.</a>
      <br> 
       <img src="/home/gouda/Desktop/Website/EtcherArchFl.png">
       <br>
 The photo above shows what the process should look like through the Etcher GUI, there are only 3 steps. The first step requires you to locate the image, .iso, .img, etc. After you upload the desired image you then insert a blank USB drive. Etcher software should auto recognize the flashdrive. 










        with Nvidia, there were many drivers that were not operable. Switching to Ubuntu gave a much wider success. Ubuntu seems to be most compatiable with hardware. If you have an older computer, a minimal distrobution would be ideal.
        I have tried Majaro, Tails, Arch, Parrot, etc but would say Ubuntu would be the best place to start.
    </font></p>
